data.name: AccessibleRole
desc: This collection of constants defines the set of possible roles of classes implementing the XAccessible interface according to the Java class javax.accessibility.AccessibleRole. The role of an object describes its generic function like \"button\", \"menu\", or \"text\". You can obtain an object's role by calling the getAccessibleRole() method of the XAccessibleContext interface.

We are using constants instead of a more typesafe enum. The reason for this is that IDL enums may not be extended. Therefore, in order to include future extensions to the set of roles we have to use constants here.
For some roles there exist two labels with the same value. Please use the one with the underscores. The other ones are somewhat deprecated and will be removed in the future.

items.name: UNKNOWN
lines: The object contains some Accessible information, but its role is not known.

items.name: ALERT
lines: Object is used to alert the user about something.

items.name: COLUMN_HEADER
lines: The header for a column of data.

items.name: CANVAS
lines: Object that can be drawn into and is used to trap events.
See also FRAME, GLASS_PANE, and LAYERED_PANE.

items.name: CHECK_BOX
lines: A choice that can be checked or unchecked and provides a separate indicator for the current state.
See also PUSH_BUTTON, TOGGLE_BUTTON, and RADIO_BUTTON.

items.name: CHECK_MENU_ITEM
lines: This role is used for check buttons that are menu items.

items.name: COLOR_CHOOSER
lines: A specialized dialog that lets the user choose a color.

items.name: COMBO_BOX
lines: A list of choices the user can select from. Also optionally allows the user to enter a choice of their own.

items.name: DATE_EDITOR
lines: A DATE_EDITOR is a component that allows users to edit date and time.

items.name: DESKTOP_ICON
lines: An iconified internal frame in a DESKTOP_PANE.

items.name: DESKTOP_PANE
lines: A pane that supports internal frames and iconified versions of those internal frames.

items.name: DIRECTORY_PANE
lines: A pane that allows the user to navigate through and select the contents of a directory. May be used by a file chooser.

items.name: DIALOG
lines: A top level window with title bar and a border. A dialog is similar to a frame, but it has fewer properties and is often used as a secondary window for an application.

items.name: DOCUMENT
lines: The view of an actual document. Its content depends on the document type.

items.name: END_NOTE
lines: Text that is used as an endnote (footnote at the end of a chapter or section.

items.name: FILE_CHOOSER
lines: A specialized dialog that displays the files in the directory and lets the user select a file, browse a different directory, or specify a filename. May use the directory pane to show the contents of a directory.

items.name: FILLER
lines: An object that fills up space in a user interface. It is often used in interfaces to tweak the spacing between components, but serves no other purpose.

items.name: FONT_CHOOSER
lines: A FONT_CHOOSER is a component that lets the user pick various attributes for fonts.

items.name: FOOTNOTE
lines: Text that is used as a footnote.

items.name: FRAME
lines: A top level window with a title bar, border, menu bar, etc. It is often used as the primary window for an application.
See also DIALOG, CANVAS, and WINDOW.

items.name: GLASS_PANE
lines: A pane that is guaranteed to be painted on top of all panes beneath it.

items.name: GROUP_BOX
lines: A GROUP_BOX is a simple container that contains a border around it and contains components inside it.

items.name: ICON
lines: A small fixed size picture, typically used to decorate components.

items.name: INTERNAL_FRAME
lines: A frame-like object that is clipped by a desktop pane. The desktop pane, internal frame, and desktop icon objects are often used to create multiple document interfaces within an application.
See also DESKTOP_ICON, DESKTOP_PANE, and FRAME.

items.name: LABEL
lines: An object used to present an icon or short string in an interface.

items.name: LAYERED_PANE
lines: A specialized pane that allows its children to be drawn in layers, providing a form of stacking order. This is usually the pane that holds the menu bar as well as the pane that contains most of the visual components in a window.

items.name: LIST
lines: An object that presents a list of objects to the user and allows the user to select one or more of them. A list is usually contained within a scroll pane.

items.name: LIST_ITEM
lines: An object that presents an element in a list. A list is usually contained within a scroll pane.

items.name: MENU
lines: An object usually found inside a menu bar that contains a list of actions the user can choose from. A menu can have any object as its children, but most often they are menu items, other menus, or rudimentary objects such as radio buttons, check boxes, or separators. For example, an application may have an \"Edit\" menu that contains menu items for \"Cut\" and \"Paste.\"
See also MENU_BAR, MENU_ITEM, SEPARATOR, RADIO_BUTTON, CHECK_BOX, and POPUP_MENU.

items.name: MENU_BAR
lines: An object usually drawn at the top of the primary dialog box of an application that contains a list of menus the user can choose from. For example, a menu bar might contain menus for \"File,\" \"Edit,\" and \"Help.\"
See also MENU, POPUP_MENU, and LAYERED_PANE.

items.name: MENU_ITEM
lines: An object usually contained in a menu that presents an action the user can choose. For example, the \"Cut\" menu item in an \"Edit\" menu would be an action the user can select to cut the selected area of text in a document.
See also MENUBAR, SEPARATOR, and POPUP_MENU.

items.name: OPTION_PANE
lines: A specialized pane whose primary use is inside a DIALOG.

items.name: PAGE_TAB
lines: An object that is a child of a page tab list. Its sole child is the panel that is to be presented to the user when the user selects the page tab from the list of tabs in the page tab list.

items.name: PAGE_TAB_LIST
lines: An object that presents a series of panels (or page tabs), one at a time, through some mechanism provided by the object. The most common mechanism is a list of tabs at the top of the panel. The children of a page tab list are all page tabs.

items.name: PANEL
lines: A generic container that is often used to group objects.

items.name: PASSWORD_TEXT
lines: A text object used for passwords, or other places where the text contents is not shown visibly to the user.

items.name: POPUP_MENU
lines: A temporary window that is usually used to offer the user a list of choices, and then hides when the user selects one of those choices.

items.name: PUSH_BUTTON
lines: An object the user can manipulate to tell the application to do something.
See also CHECK_BOX, TOGGLE_BUTTON, RADIO_BUTTON, BUTTON_MENU and BUTTON_DROPDOWN.

items.name: PROGRESS_BAR
lines: An object used to indicate how much of a task has been completed.

items.name: RADIO_BUTTON
lines: A specialized check box that will cause other radio buttons in the same group to become unchecked when this one is checked.
See also PUSH_BUTTON, TOGGLE_BUTTON, and CHECK_BOX.

items.name: RADIO_MENU_ITEM
lines: This role is used for radio buttons that are menu items.

items.name: ROW_HEADER
lines: The header for a row of data.

items.name: ROOT_PANE
lines: A specialized pane that has a glass pane and a layered pane as its children.

items.name: SCROLL_BAR
lines: An object usually used to allow a user to incrementally view a large amount of data. Usually used only by a scroll pane.

items.name: SCROLL_PANE
lines: An object that allows a user to incrementally view a large amount of information. Its children can include scroll bars and a viewport.

items.name: SHAPE
lines: Object with graphical representation used to represent content on draw pages.

items.name: SEPARATOR
lines: An object usually contained in a menu to provide a visual and logical separation of the contents in a menu. For example, the \"File\" menu of an application might contain menu items for \"Open,\" \"Close,\" and \"Exit,\" and will place a separator between \"Close\" and \"Exit\" menu items.

items.name: SLIDER
lines: An object that allows the user to select from a bounded range. For example, a slider might be used to select a number between 0 and 100.

items.name: SPIN_BOX
lines: A SPIN_BOX is a simple spinner component and its main use is for simple numbers.

items.name: SPLIT_PANE
lines: A specialized panel that presents two other panels at the same time. Between the two panels is a divider the user can manipulate to make one panel larger and the other panel smaller.

items.name: STATUS_BAR
lines: A STATUS_BAR is an simple component that can contain multiple labels of status information to the user.

items.name: TABLE
lines: An object used to present information in terms of rows and columns. An example might include a spreadsheet application.

items.name: TEXT
lines: An object that presents text to the user. The text is usually editable by the user as opposed to a label or static text.

items.name: TEXT_FRAME
lines: Collection of objects that constitute a logical text entity.

items.name: TOGGLE_BUTTON
lines: A specialized push button that can be checked or unchecked, but does not provide a separate indicator for the current state.
See also PUSH_BUTTON, CHECK_BOX and RADIO_BUTTON.

items.name: TOOL_BAR
lines: A bar or palette usually composed of push buttons or toggle buttons. It is often used to provide the most frequently used functions for an application.

items.name: TOOL_TIP
lines: An object that provides information about another object. The accessible Description property of the tool tip is often displayed to the user in a small \"help bubble\" when the user causes the mouse to hover over the object associated with the tool tip.

items.name: TREE
lines: An object used to present hierarchical information to the user. The individual nodes in the tree can be collapsed and expanded to provide selective disclosure of the tree's contents.

items.name: VIEW_PORT
lines: An object usually used in a scroll pane. It represents the portion of the entire data that the user can see. As the user manipulates the scroll bars, the contents of the viewport can change.

items.name: WINDOW
lines: A top level window with no title or border.

items.name: BUTTON_DROPDOWN
lines: The object represents a button that drops down a list of items.

items.name: BUTTON_MENU
lines: The object represents a button that drops down a menu.

items.name: CAPTION
lines: The object contains descriptive information, usually textual, about another user interface element such as a table, chart, or image.

items.name: CHART
lines: The object is a graphical depiction of quantitative data. It may contain multiple subelements whose attributes and/or description may be queried to obtain both the quantitative data and information about how the data is being presented.

items.name: EDIT_BAR
lines: A role indicating the object acts as a formula for calculating a value.

items.name: FORM
lines: The object is a container for form controls, for instance as part of a web form or user-input form within a document.

items.name: IMAGE_MAP
lines: Usually a graphic with multiple hotspots, where each hotspot can be activated resulting in the loading of another document or section of a document.

items.name: NOTE
lines: An embedded note which is not visible until activated.

items.name: PAGE
lines: An object representing a page of document content. It is used in documents which are accessed by the user on a page by page basis.

items.name: RULER
lines: An object which describes margins and tab stops, etc. for text objects which it controls.

items.name: SECTION
lines: The object is a containing instance of document content which constitutes a particular \"logical\" section of the document.

items.name: TREE_ITEM
lines: An object that presents an element in a tree

items.name: TREE_TABLE
lines: An object which represents both hierarchical and tabular information.

items.name: COMMENT
lines: An object which represents a comment.

A comment is anchored at a certain content position in the document and annotates this document content position or a certain text range of the document content. In the OpenDocument file format a comment is known as an annotation.

items.name: COMMENT_END
lines: An invisible object which represents the end position of a text range which is annotated by a comment - see COMMENT.
This object and the corresponding object representing the comment shall be in relation of type MEMBER_OF.

items.name: DOCUMENT_PRESENTATION
lines: It's an specific variation of DOCUMENT for presentations.

items.name: DOCUMENT_SPREADSHEET
lines: It's an specific variation of DOCUMENT for spreadsheets.

items.name: DOCUMENT_TEXT
lines: It's an specific variation of DOCUMENT for text.

items.name: STATIC
lines: An object that presents a brief amount of information to the user. The text is not editable by the user as opposed to a text, and not meant to have a relation with another object as opposed to a label.
